photo.description: The Dazu Rock Carvings, in Dazu county, are a series of Chinese religious sculptures and carvings, dating back as far as the 7th century A.D., depicting and influenced by Buddhist, Confucian and Taoist beliefs. Listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site, the Dazu Rock Carvings are made up of 75 protected sites containing some 50,000 statues, with over 100,000 Chinese characters forming inscriptions and epigraphs. (wikipedia) We visited the Bao Ding Mountain site, about 60 km from Chongqing

photo.description: An arhat (luohan in Chinese) is a person close to achieving enlightenment. A common tradition in Chinese Buddhism is the idea that a number of arhats remain in this world to defend the Doctrine. These are normally found in groups of sixteen or eighteen, often accompanied by attendants. Excavated at the site of Dazhong Temple, Dazu. Northern Song dynasty (AD960-1126). (c) Dazu Rock Carvings Museum, Chongqing, China ___________________________________________ Grwp o ddeg arhat (4 o 10) Person sy’n agos at oleuedigaeth yw arhat (neu luohan mewn Tsieinëeg). Un o syniadau traddodiadol cyffredin Bwdhaeth Tsieineaidd yw bod sawl arhat yn dal i fod yn y byd hwn er mwyn amddiffyn yr Athrawiaeth. Fel arfer byddant mewn grŵp o un ar bymtheg neu ddeunaw, a bydd gweision gyda nhw hefyd. Wedi’u cloddio ar safle Teml Dazhong, Dazu. Llinach Song y gogledd (OC 960-1126). (c) Amgueddfa Cerfiadau Caerreg Dazu, Chongqing, Tsieina
